      "text": "Based on the analysis of the spectral data provided:\n\n1.  **Mass Spectrometry (HRMS):** The formula is **C10H13ClO2** (Calculated [M+H]+: 201.0677, Found: 201.0675). The calculated Degree of Unsaturation (DBE) is **4**.\n2.  **1H NMR Analysis:**\n    *   **Aromatic Region:** Signals at 7.16–7.03 (m, 2H) and 6.76 (d, J = 8.4 Hz, 1H) indicate a **1,2,4-trisubstituted benzene ring**. The doublet at 6.76 ppm is shielded and has a large ortho-coupling (8.4 Hz), characteristic of a proton **ortho to an electron-donating alkoxy group** (OMe) and having one ortho neighbor.\n    *   **Side Chains:**\n        *   `3.81 (s, 3H)`: Methoxy group (-OCH3).\n        *   `3.60 (t, J = 6.3 Hz, 2H)`: Methylene group attached to oxygen (-CH2-OH).\n        *   `2.68 (t, J = 7.4 Hz, 2H)`: Benzylic methylene group (Ar-CH2-).\n        *   `1.79 – 1.86 (m, 2H)`: Middle methylene in a propyl chain.\n    *   This confirms a **3-hydroxypropyl** chain and a **methoxy** group. The third substituent is the Chlorine atom (from formula).\n3.  **13C NMR Analysis:**\n    *   Peaks at `155.99` (C-O), `131.91`, `129.77`, `126.67`, `125.32`, `111.40` (Ar-CH).\n    *   The shifts match a trisubstituted benzene. The peak at `111.40` ppm corresponds to the shielded aromatic carbon ortho to the methoxy group (matching the proton at 6.76 ppm).\n    *   Comparison of predicted chemical shifts for the two likely isomers:\n        *   **Case A (3-(3-chloro-4-methoxyphenyl)propan-1-ol):** Predicts C-Cl (ortho to OMe) around **121 ppm** and C-Propyl (para to OMe) around **130 ppm**. The spectrum lacks a peak near 121 ppm.\n        *   **Case C (3-(5-chloro-2-methoxyphenyl)propan-1-ol):** Predicts C-Propyl (ortho to OMe) around **124-125 ppm** and C-Cl (para to OMe) around **127 ppm**. This aligns very well with the observed peaks at **125.32** and **126.67** ppm.\n4.  **Conclusion:** The data strongly supports the structure **3-(5-chloro-2-methoxyphenyl)propan-1-ol** (also named 2-(3-hydroxypropyl)-4-chloroanisole). The coupling pattern (d, 8.4 Hz) indicates H6 is ortho to OMe and adjacent to H5, while H3 is isolated, which fits this 1,2,4-substitution pattern (1-OMe, 2-propyl, 4-Cl).\n\nFINAL_RESULT:\n  UUID: 52d634fa-2435-45eb-8204-83081f8e0c62\n  PREDICTED_SMILES: COc1c(CCCO)cc(Cl)cc1\n  CONFIDENCE: 0.95\n  REASON_BRIEF: 1H NMR indicates a 1,2,4-trisubstituted benzene with a methoxy group and a 3-hydroxypropyl chain. The 13C chemical shifts (specifically the ipso carbons at 125.3 and 126.7 ppm) strongly favor the 1-methoxy-2-propyl-4-chloro isomer over other regiochemical possibilities.",
